                    <h3 style="padding:0;width:100%;font-family:Georgia, 'Times New Roman', Times, serif;font-weight:700;font-size:16px;color:#93888F;line-height:23.1px;text-align: left;margin:0;text-transform:uppercase;">Ride-hailing</h3>
                </div>
                <div style="width:100%; background-color: transparent; box-sizing:border-box;">
                    <h3 style="width:100%; font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;font-size:16px;margin:0;padding-bottom:16px;font-weight:700;color:#28121F;line-height:20px;text-transform:capitalize;letter-spacing:-0.32px;text-align:left;box-sizing:border-box;">Uber plans to scale Uber Moto fleet in South Africa to 300,000</h3>
                    <div style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size:16px;line-height:25.6px;margin:0;padding-bottom:16px;box-sizing:border-box;">
<figure style="width: 100%;padding-bottom:16px;text-align:left;margin:0">

<a href="https://techcabal.com/category/newsletters/tc-daily/">
<img decoding="async" 
     	loading="lazy" src="https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2025/08/expand-meme.jpg" width="100%" height="auto" style="object-fit: cover"></a>
<figcaption style="color:#808080;font-size:12px;font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;line-height:19.8px;padding-top:6px;font-weight:400">Image source: Andertoons</figcaption>
</figure>
                        
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;">Uber, the ride-hailing platform, wants to <a href="https://mybroadband.co.za/news/motoring/638170-uber-wants-300000-motorcycles-carrying-passengers-in-south-africa.html" style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">grow its motorcycle rider network</a> in South Africa to 300,000 over the next decade. This follows the company&rsquo;s recent announcement to <a href="https://techcabal.com/2026/04/01/techcabal-daily-uber-money/" style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">invest R5 billion ($293 million)</a> into its South Africa operations.&nbsp;</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;">The money is earmarked to scale its electric vehicle (EV) fleet and charging infrastructure while improving driver compensation, but it looks like two-wheelers will get a big share of that attention.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;"><strong>State of play: </strong>Uber Moto, the company&rsquo;s more nimble two-wheeler service, already operates in South Africa and <a href="https://valternative.africa/uber-package-unveils-a-global-first-in-cape-town-with-a-fully-electric-fleet/" style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">partners with local EV infrastructure player Valternative</a> on a swap-and-go battery system for electric bikes. That makes it easier to add riders quickly and keep them on the road longer without high upfront costs.&nbsp;</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;">Uber has also said that a portion of its budget will go toward onboarding riders, which fits with its pattern in other markets where it pushes two-wheelers and EVs as its first lever for growth.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;"><strong>Between the lines: </strong>Across major markets, Uber is shifting to an EV-first playbook, especially on two-wheelers. In Kenya, it has <a href="https://www.reuters.com/sustainability/uber-rolls-out-electric-bike-fleet-kenya-its-first-africa-2023-08-31/" style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">rolled out</a> thousands of electric motorcycles, and in Nigeria, it has <a href="https://techcabal.com/2022/01/26/bike-hailing-in-ibadan/" style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">experimented with two-wheelers</a> in Ibadan as a cheaper, more flexible format for short trips.&nbsp;</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;">Yet, in South Africa, even as it talks up EVs and long-term investment, Uber still has not secured the e-licence needed to fully plug into the country&rsquo;s formal public transport system.</p>
